1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:27,800
 Good morning, distinguished guests, ladies and gentlemen. Thank you so much for joining us for this very specific conversation as we talk about energy security and energy transition. We do have a short video to play for you first, and I will ask our speakers to join us on stage right now, but we are going to just do a little bit of scene setting for you as we roll out this video.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,000
 Thank you.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:01,000
 I'll see you next time.

4
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:02,000
 I'll see you next time.

5
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 Let's look back. Russia's invasion of Ukraine brought an end to abundant and relatively cheap natural gas imports to Europe. Energy prices in Europe spiked, and the continent experienced its biggest energy crisis in 50 years. Though prices have since fallen, they remain about three times higher than before the COVID-19 pandemic. Now, Europe's reliance on Russian natural gas has come to a grinding halt.

6
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 CESI countries were among the most dependent on gas imports from Russia before the war. Indeed, for some countries, these imports were the only source of gas. So, it's not surprising that the energy crisis has fueled inflation, especially in Europe's CESI economies, reduced household purchasing power, and slowed economic activity sharply across the continent. European governments responded swiftly with a range of measures

7
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:15,000
 with a range of measures to diversify supply, improve trans-European energy infrastructure, and reduce demand. Gas producers, such as Norway, Qatar, the U.S., and Algeria, stepped in to fill the supply gap left by Russia.

8
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 Motivated by higher prices, policy changes, and helped by a warmer winter, households and firms reduced their gas consumption. Most EU countries introduced or extended tax breaks, price caps, targeted transfers, or energy vouchers. These measures

9
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:53,000
 successfully reduce the energy costs passed through. But they come with undesirable side effects. They delay the necessary adjustment in demand. And while they benefit consumers in the country where they are introduced, they may lead to higher wholesale prices across the continent, hurting consumers in other countries.

10
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 So, these measures should be carefully designed and phased out as energy prices fall. Challenging times lie ahead. Energy-intensive firms that are bound by long-term contracts signed during the height of the crisis will likely remain strained for some time.

11
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 While EU countries have emerged from this past winter with higher than average levels of stored gas, replenishing those stores without Russian supplies could be harder this year.

12
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:39,000
 At the same time, the world's largest gas importer, China, has ended its Zero-Covid strategy and the periodic shutdowns and reduction in Chinese energy demand it created. This could lead to tighter global markets.

13
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 Due to infrastructure bottlenecks, any gas shortage next winter may be distributed unequally, with the landlocked countries in Central and Eastern Europe being the most vulnerable. Energy security will remain a top priority in the years ahead.

14
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 The crisis also highlighted the complex interactions between energy security and climate objectives. Faced with emergency, some countries have substituted gas with much more carbon-intensive fuels,

15
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 such as coal, at the cost of increased greenhouse gas emissions in the short term.

16
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 In the medium term, however, there are clear synergies between energy security and the green transition, as reducing greenhouse gas emissions requires more renewables and less reliance on fossil fuels.

17
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 That's why it's critical that governments ramp up policies to incentivize the transition, including carbon pricing, which remains in its infancy across SESI.

18
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 With so many moving parts, questions remain: Are there signs or risks of deindustrialization as Europe loses competitiveness against other regions of the world with reliable access to cheap energy?

19
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:56,000
 What more can be done to secure sufficient energy supplies from reliable sources over the medium term?

20
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 How best can the green energy transition be shaped to also enhance energy security?

21
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,000
 So key questions already addressed there.

22
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
 Now let me welcome to the stage our panel today.

23
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 Alfred Kammer, Director, European Department, International Monetary Fund.

24
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 Jan Svejner, Director, Centre on Global Economy and Governance, School of International and Public Affairs at Columbia University.

25
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:44,000
 Paula Pino, Director for Just Transition: Consumers, Energy Efficiency and Innovation, Director General for Energy at the European Commission.

26
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 And finally, Olga Hakkova, who is Deputy Director, European Energy Security at the Atlantic Council.

27
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:12,000
 So we're just going to start a little bit broad and take a little bit of a litmus test from the audience, that is you, as to where you think we're at this point in energy security.

28
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:20,000
 I mean, there have been so many deep and complex topics and we cover them every day on CNBC.

29
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 What is very much in the backdrop at this point is where we go to from here.

30
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 I mean, we've been debating macroeconomic policy, where the Fed, where the ECB are going, what that does in terms of tightening credit conditions more.

31
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 I don't know whether you follow this, but we're talking about AI, generative AI and how disruptive that will be on economies, but also front and centre.

32
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 What happens next when it comes to energy security?

33
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 Who in this room thinks that we're through the energy crisis?

34
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
 I'll ask you to stand up.

35
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 Does anyone believe we're done?

36
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 We're through winter.

37
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 We're through the height of the prices.

38
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 Do you think we're done when it comes to energy security?

39
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 So everybody then by default means that they believe we're all in an energy crisis still.

40
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 That is overwhelming or nobody felt like standing up.

41
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 So I guess you have to stand up now.

42
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 So the room does actually believe we're in an energy crisis.

43
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,000
 Feel free to stand up.

44
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 You can't sit on the fence here.

45
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 You have to take a position.

46
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
 So that means everybody has to stand up.

47
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 Okay, this is a good start because we are going to kick off a discussion here first up.

48
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 And we will be taking some questions from the audience.

49
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 So that does require you to be engaged and listen very attentively to the panel here.

50
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 I'm just going to let you know too that we have a special guest in the audience.

51
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 We have Peter Wood, who is Chief Energy Advisor at Shell.

52
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 Peter, if I can ask you to stand up.

53
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 So we might just bring a microphone over to Peter as well if we can.

54
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 We've got a live microphone here and if Peter could have that microphone

55
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 because we're going to ask him to weigh in too to some of the discussion.

56
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:01,000
 Well, welcome everyone.

57
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
 Thank you so much for joining us.

58
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 Alfred, if I can just switch to you on this topic as we discussed and just start a little bit broad here.

59
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 How have countries in Europe adjusted to dwindling gas supplies from Russia?

60
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 Where do you think we're at on this journey to achieve energy security and energy transition?

61
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 I think as the previous speakers have pointed out, we were faced with an unprecedented set of crises.

62
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 We came out of the pandemic and we had a very strong exit.

63
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 And I think one of the hallmarks of this exit was it was a result of very strong policies during the pandemic.

64
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 And then we were hit by the Russia's war in Ukraine with a massive energy crisis.

65
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 And we are still living through these repercussions and low growth this year.

66
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 The high inflation we are seeing is a large result of this intervention.

67
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 But it could have been worse and if not for policy action.

68
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 When you're looking at the outset last year, natural gas dependency of Europe, 84% imported.

69
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 40% of that coming from Russia.

70
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 The biggest concern was for the landlocked countries, Slovakia, Czech Republic, Hungary, but also Austria, Italy and Germany.

71
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 Because in the case of a Russian gas shutdown, they could actually have experienced a physical shortage.

72
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 And that meant rationing of gas.

73
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 That was avoided.

74
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 That would have led to a much worse outcome.

75
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 And it was avoided because of policy action.

76
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:58,000
 On the supply side, what happened was a concerted effort to keep increased gas imports through pipelines.

77
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 But also to expand on the LNG side.

78
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 And when you're looking at what happened is Russian gas was reduced by 80 billion cubic meters.

79
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 55 billion cubic meters of that was made up by new supply and new imports.

80
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 That was part of the equation, but it was not all of the equation.

81
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 And the other part was really on the demand side.

82
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 And what happened on the demand side was largely going through the price mechanism.

83
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 And therefore it's important that prices speak and prices cause action.

84
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 What we had was a response on the demand side, which was also a reduction of 55 billion cubic meters.

85
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 And that came from a shutdown of production of some of the energy intensive products, like a fertilizer.

86
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:54,000
 25% of that was made up.

87
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 40% came up from efficiency gains by households and firms.

88
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 And then we were lucky.

89
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 And a third of that demand shortfall was explained by a mild winter.

90
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 And what it helped us to do is not only come through the winter, but at the beginning of this year, storage levels were double as high as they were usually coming out of a winter.

91
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 And so we are set up, I think, going into the next winter with a relatively good way.

92
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
 We just kicked off the session talking about the challenge that lies ahead.

93
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:40,000
 I think about how much prices have moved, even on the oil side, Brent at 125 in June last year, trading either side of 80 these days.

94
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 When you look at the European gas price, we peaked at 3.22 dollars per megawatt hour, returning to more normal levels.

95
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 The price action looks like it's crisis averted.

96
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
 But what's the risk from here?

97
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 What keeps you awake at night as you look forward in coming months?

98
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 I think what we need to focus also on was part of the government response, which was dealing with the cost of living crisis.

99
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 That was an important part for government to think about protecting the most vulnerable population.

100
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 And government overall have done a good job, too much so to some extent.

101
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:24,000
 When we are looking at energy packages, the cost for 22, 23, 2.7 percent of GDP.

102
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:34,000
 When we are looking at protecting the most vulnerable, 40 percent of the population, we could have done that in a targeted way with 1.5 percent of GDP.

103
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 more cheaper, better targeted, reaching the most vulnerable.

104
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
 And why is that a concern? Not only because of the fiscal side.

105
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:50,000
 It is also a concern because that adds to demand, that adds to inflation, that adds to centre bank needing to fight inflation.

106
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:54,000
 And I think that is a concern we have.

107
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 Olga, let me switch to you.

108
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:58,000
 We've got fiscal subsidies at play.

109
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:00,000
 Market pricing has come down.

110
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 We've diversified supply chains.

111
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:04,000
 We've ramped up storage.

112
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:06,000
 Why are we still in an energy crisis?

113
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:12,000
 Because there's a lot that can happen in the next several months, even the next three to four to five months.

114
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 So a couple of unpredictable variables that we're keeping an eye on.

115
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:21,000
 There is no guarantee that Russian flows will keep going through Ukraine or I would even push as far as even Turkey.

116
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:31,000
 Russia could be in a position where there could be some additional decisions made if they are in a certain desperate spot to create additional pressure on Europe.

117
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 There is a scenario where these supplies stop flowing through Ukraine.

118
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:43,000
 Now, compared to last year, we are nowhere in the same position in terms of the transformation that needs to happen.

119
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 But when we're talking about shortages and multiple variables happening at the same time, it could still put additional strain.

120
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:58,000
 Let's take a look at exacerbated impacts on weather patterns driven by climate change.

121
00:13:58,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 We got lucky.

122
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 This was said multiple times today with the warmer winter.

123
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,000
 We could still have heat waves.

124
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 We could have cold snaps.

125
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:11,000
 We could have impacts on hydro or other energy production.

126
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:14,000
 And of course that interconnects to nuclear production across Europe.

127
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 That even interconnects on how well coal is delivered across Europe and across the world sometimes too.

128
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:27,000
 There could be some technical outages that have nothing to do with malign actors or climate implications.

129
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 There could be cyber security concerns or cyber attacks on and there could be further critical infrastructure threats or even on the extreme.

130
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:43,000
 You know, look at what happened in North Stream 1, North Stream 2.

131
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 There could be threats to the critical infrastructure across the world.

132
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 So we can't over-prepare for the upcoming winter.

133
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 So all of these things do keep me up at night.

134
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:58,000
 All of these things, I don't feel like we can say that we're fully ready.

135
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:04,000
 I think we need to continue over-preparing and looking at every single scenario and assuming that everything will go wrong.

136
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:07,000
 And then we prepared for that and then we're going to be okay.

137
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:09,000
 Jan, let me bring you in.

138
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:12,000
 There's another layer here and that's the macroeconomic dynamics.

139
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 We've just seen a whole bunch of survey data suggesting that we have manufacturing contraction.

140
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:24,000
 Even in core economies in Europe from France to Italy, Germany in recession.

141
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:29,000
 We are now setting up for a challenging few months with interest rates also going up.

142
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 The challenge of energy security on top of that with already shrinking growth.

143
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 Just set the scene for us.

144
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:40,000
 How difficult an environment are we looking at as we battle an energy crisis still?

145
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:42,000
 It is a very difficult environment.

146
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 I agree with what Alfred and Olga mentioned.

147
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 Those are very important points and we have to realise that Europe is one of the slower growing or more vulnerable regions of the world.

148
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:59,000
 The US is doing quite well compared to Europe and has been doing in the past.

149
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:04,000
 China, as we saw, may be coming out of a slow period.

150
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:12,000
 So if demand goes up from these countries, we can expect that prices of energy will go up with that.

151
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:21,000
 OPEC is meeting in Vienna as we speak, trying to figure out can they somehow manage to raise prices by withholding production.

152
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 So I think that we are in a very difficult situation and Europe in particular is quite vulnerable and CSE parts of it are indeed under pressure and will be under pressure.

153
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 So the demand conditions will be important, supply will be crucial and development of alternative sources of course will be very, very important.

154
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 So I would say we are in a very uncertain type situation and going back to the earlier speakers, I think the question of adaptability, dynamism, resilience will be crucial.

155
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:04,000
 And in Europe we have to count on the possibility of countries teetering on the verge of recession during this year.

156
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:13,000
 Paula, let me turn to you. An energy crisis still looms. What are the biggest risks? How will the impacts be felt from here?

157
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 How will the impacts be felt from here if we don't get it right?

158
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:23,000
 Well, we really need to look back and also see lessons learned, right?

159
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:42,000
 And when you see where we started from and we were faced with a second crisis and we were in a context of Green Deal, European Green Deal transition to the first climate neutral continent in the world and then hits COVID.

160
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:47,000
 And that was the first time that the Green Deal was put into question and said this is the end of it.

161
00:17:47,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 And then we had the next generation EU which really put forward unprecedented financial means as was said already today including by the Prime Minister which created unprecedented possibilities.

162
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:06,000
 And then hit the energy crisis and again this is the end of the European Green Deal.

163
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:21,000
 And not really. And Alfred described very well what were the sort of measures that were put into place in terms of short term but also in terms of longer term, the structural measures but also the emergency measures.

164
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:38,000
 and we're not out yet but what we learned from last year is that through this combination of emergency measures on the supply, on the demand, on the infrastructure, on the prices, we came out and we survived the winter.

165
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 We're not out of the woods yet but hopefully we also learned a number of very, very valid lessons during this winter.

166
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 For instance we all of the sudden discovered the potential of energy efficiency.

167
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:59,000
 Very interesting to hear from industry that they now looked into how can I manufacture more efficiently.

168
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:04,000
 There hadn't been an incentive to do so before because gas prices were pretty low.

169
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:06,000
 So why even look for alternatives?

170
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:19,000
 I want to hope that these lessons are here to stay and lead to structural changes which will really allow us to be on a much more resilient path as we go forward.

171
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:26,000
 Also when we see the deployment of renewable energy over the past year we have broken records.

172
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:36,000
 We have added 47 percent of additional capacity in solar power, 46 percent in wind compared to the year before.

173
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:39,000
 Really massive that we had not counted on.

174
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 This is here to stay.

175
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:53,000
 So this will have a long lasting structural impact on our resilience and will make decarbonization converge with energy security interests.

176
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 The theme of the conference is policy making in choppy waters and it's felt like choppy waters for a long time I think in Europe.

177
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:03,000
 More recently perhaps even a storm.

178
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:05,000
 So setting course in a storm.

179
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:06,000
 The direction we're going.

180
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:11,000
 Europe is heading towards net zero greenhouse gas emissions by 2050.

181
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:17,000
 When you consider the dynamics that we've faced war in Ukraine, very tough economic conditions as well.

182
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 Is the current energy crisis helping speed up the transition?

183
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:26,000
 Or in fact, is it providing hurdles to achieving the goal?

184
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:33,000
 As said, Karen, twice already this path was put into question, right?

185
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,000
 Through COVID and then through the energy crisis.

186
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:45,000
 And every time we seem to come out stronger and having really, instead of de-accelerating, we have actually accelerated.

187
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:53,000
 In terms of the structural measures, we had in place already the negotiation of the energy efficiency directive, the renewables directive.

188
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:57,000
 And we proposed, the European Commission proposed to increase the targets.

189
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:15,000
 And so is that actually, as a result of the negotiation with the Council, with the European Parliament, we came out with more ambitious targets than was initially foreseen as a result of the repower EU, as a result of the need to accelerate the independence of inputs of fossil fuels.

190
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:27,000
 The same in terms of targets for deployment of heat pumps, for instance, of solar, of wind.

191
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 And so we really are putting into place also structural measures, which will actually accelerate.

192
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 I think nobody dared to believe only one and a half year ago that we would manage to accelerate the energy transition in the way we have.

193
00:21:46,000 --> 00:22:03,000
 And this is the irony of this war in Ukraine and of the perpetrator of the war in Ukraine, that it's having an impact which is absolutely contrary to the interests of what was the main supplier of fossil fuels to Europe for many, many years and decades.

194
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:08,000
 Alfred, it did feel as though Europe had the jump on energy transition.

195
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:10,000
 There was a window of hope there.

196
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:17,000
 Then the Americans came up with a very big package, the Inflation Reduction Act, and it felt as though they've stolen the lion's share of investment now.

197
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 They have the jump on Europe.

198
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:22,000
 What do you make of where we stand at this point?

199
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:28,000
 Do you think that the conditions are helping energy transition, or are we now effectively overtaken by the Americans?

200
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:29,000
 Yeah.

201
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:36,000
 First of all, good that we got a push on the green transition, because we needed to move.

202
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:41,000
 Russia's gas shutoff triggered an acceleration of that move.

203
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 Good.

204
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 Good also that the U.S. is moving, because Europe cannot do it alone.

205
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:52,000
 Europe has global emissions of between 7% and 9% of the world total.

206
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:55,000
 You need the U.S. to move, and the U.S. is moving.

207
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 That is also good.

208
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:07,000
 But we also need to remember this is a global common good we are trying to protect, and we need to have more than just Europe and the U.S.

209
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:28,000
 We are advocating globally as a coordinating mechanism, as Kristalina said, a global carbon price to give certainty to investors, but also to have a multilateral response, a common response, including China, including India, and other emitters, in order to have a global solution.

210
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:38,000
 Subsidies, as in the IRA, they can help in particular circumstances, but we need to avoid a subsidy war.

211
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:41,000
 So in the end, we need global coordination.

212
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 That's utopia, though.

213
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:50,000
 When we've got the director of the CIA flying into China, trying to reset relations with the Chinese, we don't have global coordination.

214
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:53,000
 We have a trade war playing out, one that could get worse from here.

215
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:56,000
 So there is no global coordination on this.

216
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:03,000
 I think we, especially the IMF as a multilateral organization, we are driving to avoid fragmentation.

217
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:07,000
 Fragmentation, economic fragmentation, is going to be costly for everybody.

218
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:17,000
 If you are looking at the global common good trade, if you're looking at the payment system, if you're looking at dealing with climate change, you need global solutions.

219
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:24,000
 And that means even after you have geopolitical tensions, you need to come together in order to tackle these problems.

220
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:28,000
 I need to strive to get this done and not to have economic fragmentation.

221
00:24:28,000 --> 00:24:29,000
 Jan, come in here.

222
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:30,000
 Yeah, sure.

223
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 Look, I think that as much coordination, as much cooperation as we can achieve, obviously very, very desirable.

224
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:41,000
 I think that there are centrifugal tendencies.

225
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:45,000
 I think that some countries are definitely sort of going their own way.

226
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:54,000
 We see it in the lack of agreement on how to approach the war in Ukraine on the part of big economies, be it Brazil, be it South Africa and so on.

227
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:57,000
 So a lot of uncertainty there as well.

228
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:01,000
 I think that the U.S. is moving now very decisively.

229
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:07,000
 Europe has to take that into account and hopefully collaborate, cooperate, but there will be some competition.

230
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:12,000
 There are some European firms that are already moving to the United States and that may continue.

231
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 So it's something that's for Europe to lose, so to speak.

232
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 But I think that hopefully it will be more positive than negative.

233
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:26,000
 But we have to realize that Europe has been losing competitiveness for a while, for a long time.

234
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:31,000
 We are talking about it now as a phenomenon, but it's been here for decades, right?

235
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:36,000
 The European economy was more than a quarter of the world economy, now heading towards 15%.

236
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 While the U.S. is keeping for 40, 50 years at a quarter, 25% of the world economy, China and other countries growing dramatically.

237
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:53,000
 So Europe really is facing a challenge both in the immediate sense and in the sense of, you know, what do we do in the long run?

238
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:55,000
 How do we achieve the dynamism?

239
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:00,000
 How do we, in fact, create the next wave technologically, et cetera?

240
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:05,000
 Or at least how do we ride the crest of the wave rather than being behind, right?

241
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:08,000
 So that's, I think, really a big challenge here.

242
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:10,000
 Paula, you wanted to jump in there.

243
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:13,000
 Yes, because this is the right transfer.

244
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:25,000
 In fact, as we've been dealing with this trilemma between decarbonization, energy security, just transition, which is really difficult to reconcile, as we've seen.

245
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 And as we're finding a way to reconcile it, and then comes the fourth aspect, which is, well, and how do we ensure competitiveness of EU industry within this?

246
00:26:38,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 And that is what's triggered the European Commission recently to put on the table legislation, so-called Net Zero Industry Act, which is precisely about identifying the technologies where we do need to have industry in place in Europe, which boosts the production, and which onshores some of the production of some of the technologies needed for the energy transition.

247
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:10,000
 Before the energy transition, in terms of clean energy.

248
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 Now, the starting point is challenging, because we know energy prices still remain higher than compared to other parts of the world, so that's clearly not a benefit.

249
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:47,000
 So we need to create a set of conditions which make it attractive, and we have the seeds, we have the quality, we have the size of the market, we have a whole of the European Union within a single market, but we need to now also tackle this fourth element, which is the competitiveness of the European industry.

250
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:49,000
 Olga, let me get you in here.

251
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 Yeah, so a couple of thoughts here.

252
00:27:51,000 --> 00:28:00,000
 I don't think this needs to be a zero-sum game in terms of, you know, either a business continues thriving here in Europe, or they shot operations and they move to United States.

253
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:16,000
 I think it's all of the above, but I think it's also diving into the realities of some of the features, and there's cooperation and talks happening at the highest level on incentives coordination, and figuring out where are the areas where actual tensions exist, and how do we mitigate them in tangible ways.

254
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 And one of those conversations is around making sure that the local content requirements for Aira, that some of the European production of critical minerals can participate in that, in that way European business, US businesses, US consumers can purchase, you know, whether it's vehicles or other solutions, other clean energy solutions, that can participate in the critical mineral supply chain that's produced in Europe as well.

255
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:50,000
 And that's just one example of where we can use treasury guidance to fine-tune Aira.

256
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:53,000
 To a certain extent, there's, of course, only so much that you can do.

257
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:55,000
 It's not going to be re-legislated.

258
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:01,000
 You know, it's there to stay, but we can find ways to make it better and to work better together across these.

259
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:08,000
 Because there's no way that things like the critical mineral supply chain issues will be solved by the US or by Europe on its own.

260
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:20,000
 And to be frank, if we look at the projections even this year and next year, clean energy deployment is set to increase by a third in the next couple of years, just the next couple of years.

261
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:31,000
 So we're going to have shortage of materials, not just, you know, in terms of issues with decoupling from Chinese supply chain, but globally, we're going to have to do all of the above.

262
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:39,000
 We're going to continue to figure out a way to work with Chinese supply chain while establishing our own in US, in Europe, and working together in third countries.

263
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:52,000
 And that includes improving labor standards, and that includes improving environmental standards of how these critical minerals not only are mined, but also produced, manufactured, processed.

264
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000
 And some of that will have to happen in US and Europe.

265
00:29:55,000 --> 00:30:04,000
 And that's a tough conversation for communities that might not be ready to see some of those plants or mines in their backyards.

266
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:10,000
 They might want to see the clean energy products, but they might not be ready to see that full supply chain conversation.

267
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:19,000
 Olga, let me ask you directly then, is the trade war with China detrimental for energy transition in Europe?

268
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 If we let it, if we let it become a true war, right, or we can take a different approach and once again, take a realistic look at where we need to be in our supply chains for clean energy, critical minerals, critical materials.

269
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:40,000
 How much of that China will continue supplying?

270
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:44,000
 And realistically, how much of that can be ramped up here?

271
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:46,000
 Because we have to do these things in parallel.

272
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:53,000
 We can't pick one or the other and say we will fully decouple, and in two years we're going to produce all of our critical materials at home.

273
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,000
 That is just, that's not feasible.

274
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:57,000
 You know, it would be wonderful to live in the world with that.

275
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:59,000
 There is a real pathway to get there.

276
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:01,000
 But I don't see one.

277
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:04,000
 We also can't just sit on our hands and say, you know what?

278
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:06,000
 China is just too efficient.

279
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:10,000
 You know, these products are way too cheap for us to ever even consider competing with them.

280
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:17,000
 So we must just give up and not even try to supplement it with our own production at home.

281
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:23,000
 I want to turn to Peter and get the industry perspective because you're dealing with the Inflation Reduction Act of a day.

282
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:27,000
 You are considering where those investment decisions go as a corporation.

283
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:33,000
 Just weigh in here on some of the things we've been talking about, and of course, this trade war between the United States and China.

284
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:34,000
 Thank you.

285
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:40,000
 I don't like to talk about wars, so we'll leave that to one side.

286
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:44,000
 Look, industry moves where the returns are.

287
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:50,000
 So clearly there's strong signals from the United States at the moment.

288
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:53,000
 But there are also signals that Europe is moving as well.

289
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:55,000
 And these sorts of things don't play out overnight.

290
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:57,000
 They play out over a decade or more.

291
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:03,000
 You know, a typical large industrial investment has got, you know, three to seven years of gestation period,

292
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 and then it's going to be around for 25 years.

293
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:09,000
 So you need a bit more than just, you know, one overnight signal.

294
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:16,000
 So, you know, I think we're expecting a bit of a response from Europe, and I think the capital market will kind of respond to that.

295
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:23,000
 What I think is we need to be a bit more careful of is just how long all this is going to take to play out.

296
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:31,000
 So if we come back to natural gas, the production of natural gas in Europe is declining at a far faster rate than demand will decline,

297
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:34,000
 even in a rapid decarbonization scenario.

298
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:36,000
 So there's going to be a gap to fill.

299
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:40,000
 So Europe is going to be dependent on LNG imports for a while more to come.

300
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:46,000
 And that leaves Europe exposed, as long as it's buying on short-term contract basis, which it is at the moment.

301
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:51,000
 It leaves Europe exposed to higher prices, and particularly weather.

302
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:56,000
 So I can't emphasize enough the weather this winter is going to be really important.

303
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:59,000
 In fact, it's the weather within about 500 kilometers of Brussels.

304
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:00,000
 It's as simple as that.

305
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:04,000
 If you have a very cold start of the winter, November, December,

306
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:11,000
 and those storage levels fall lower, and you become dependent on just-in-time delivery of LNG,

307
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:14,000
 and the market tightens.

308
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:19,000
 And if it was a cold winter in China, for example, all of a sudden you're really in a steep competition.

309
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:21,000
 And that could drive prices higher.

310
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:26,000
 And this sort of threat of higher prices could be around for the next two or three winters.

311
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:31,000
 Before, the policy levers that are in place now have had more time to have a bigger impact.

312
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:33,000
 So the efficiency methods will continue to improve.

313
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:36,000
 The build-out of renewables will continue to grow.

314
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:40,000
 Sourcing of alternative forms of natural gas, a bit more pipeline from here and there.

315
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:42,000
 Those will all improve.

316
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:44,000
 But we remain exposed.

317
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:53,000
 That's extraordinary, because there is some market chatter that intraday prices could flip to zero, below zero, over the course of the next couple of months.

318
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:57,000
 It's not the base case scenario, but it's a possibility, right?

319
00:33:57,000 --> 00:33:58,000
 That's right.

320
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:03,000
 But let's be, let's be, we've got intraday prices, spot prices here and now, and then we've got the futures curve.

321
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:10,000
 So if you look at the futures curve, I haven't checked on my phone this morning, but you see the prices are higher for this coming winter and for the two winters ahead.

322
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:13,000
 So the markets are signaling, could be tight.

323
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:18,000
 They're not very high, but of course a lot of natural gas is bought in longer term contracts.

324
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:25,000
 But if it gets cold and you have to go out and start buying boatloads of LNG, that's what drives your price right back up again.

325
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:28,000
 And it transmits the price all over the world.

326
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:38,000
 So Europe bid up LNG prices last year and those who are less fortunate weren't able to afford it and they didn't have energy or they moved to coal.

327
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:43,000
 Before we let you just take a rest for a minute, can I ask you about the interconnections in Europe?

328
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:49,000
 We just heard from the Prime Minister talking about some of the decisions that have been made at a government level here in Croatia.

329
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:52,000
 But we know that those decisions have been happening right across Europe.

330
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:59,000
 Big debate around the Iberian Peninsula, how gas flows are being brought into Europe from that side.

331
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:03,000
 Also from Azerbaijan through Turkey into parts of Europe.

332
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:09,000
 How far do you think the interconnection story has gone at this point and how much more work is there still to do?

333
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:16,000
 So on the gas side, you had gas coming into the center of the continent from Russia, which is where it's cold.

334
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:23,000
 And of course that's stopped now and LNG comes into the coastline so you need to get the gas from the coast back to the interior.

335
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:27,000
 I think that that can be done small amounts of investment.

336
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:30,000
 What bothers me more now is the electricity grid.

337
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:38,000
 Because the demand for electricity is likely to more or less double in the next 30 years as we electrify cars and home heating and so forth.

338
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:47,000
 And that is going to require large scale distribution systems offshore, bringing it onshore, not too difficult.

339
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:50,000
 Across countries, pylons, very difficult.

340
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:55,000
 And then strengthening of the local distribution grid, which is not difficult per se.

341
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:58,000
 People see the wires, but it's a lot of activity.

342
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:07,000
 So we need to be thinking about distribution companies, which many have not seen large increases in power demand for a long time.

343
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:13,000
 They need to reconfigure themselves from maintaining the grid to expanding the grid.

344
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:16,000
 Paula, this puts the ball on the tee for you.

345
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:17,000
 Thank you, Karen.

346
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:26,000
 And building on that, I mean, on the interconnection, be it for gas, for electricity, it's been years that the European Union is working on that.

347
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:31,000
 And we have reaped the benefits of all that work precisely over the last year.

348
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 What the Prime Minister mentioned today, the Kirk LNG terminal, for instance, which is playing a decisive role now to bring in LNG,

349
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:41,000
 but also interconnected between Poland and Lithuania.

350
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:48,000
 The Klaipeda LNG terminal is now helping bringing in.

351
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:57,000
 The interconnector between Greece and Bulgaria, which was long on discussion and construction and now is commissioned,

352
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:01,000
 really now brought the benefits of all this long-term investment.

353
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:02,000
 And we're not done yet.

354
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:07,000
 And that is still one of the issues we need to complete, both on gas and electricity.

355
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:09,000
 Gas were practically done.

356
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:12,000
 Electricity, there's still a lot to be done.

357
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:14,000
 And we need to learn the lessons.

358
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:22,000
 Precisely as we increase the need to electrify with all this renewable energy that we want to bring in,

359
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:26,000
 we will have to match it in terms of the grid capacity.

360
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:32,000
 So we need to act swiftly and now because we know these things do take time.

361
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:41,000
 So we need to now really focus on investing in the electricity grid to really make it possible for this decarbonisation to take place

362
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:46,000
 and for this increasing electrification of the energy system that we are preparing.

363
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:52,000
 Again, in order to ensure our resilience in terms of both decarbonisation but also energy security.

364
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:55,000
 Olga, where does that investment come from?

365
00:37:55,000 --> 00:37:58,000
 That is the billion-dollar question, right?

366
00:37:58,000 --> 00:37:59,000
 Or several billion-dollar questions.

367
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:07,000
 In the past, and I don't think the Commission gets enough credit for, I mean, the massive amount of work that was done over the last couple of decades and the built-out of infrastructure.

368
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:13,000
 But I agree with you, you know, there's still some gaps, particularly for land-locked countries.

369
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:35,000
 And the trick there is you do need kind of either EU level or some kind of a broader level risk management and investment mechanisms because at a national level, you know, if you were to build your part of the pipeline and then just hope that, you know, the other countries in that network continue doing so in a timely manner and do it right, you know, that's when it becomes complex.

370
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:50,000
 And we're not done yet, you know, like Hungary, Slovakia, Czech Republic, and a lot of this area, they're still hungry for interconnections in order to truly diversify permanently, not just for a couple of years, but truly permanently diversify and be interconnected.

371
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:52,000
 And I agree on the great conversation.

372
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:53,000
 I do think it's a sleeping crisis.

373
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:55,000
 I think that's going to catch us off guard.

374
00:38:55,000 --> 00:38:59,000
 I completely agree here in a couple of years.

375
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:00,000
 Yeah.

376
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:06,000
 Just to add on that, we need European solutions because we are talking about a single market.

377
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:09,000
 We are talking about electricity grid.

378
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:11,000
 We are talking about gas infrastructure.

379
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:21,000
 And I think that requires not national responses, but European responses, including through European funding.

380
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:24,000
 I think that's one very important part.

381
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:28,000
 But I would add one other element when we are talking about the private sector.

382
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:33,000
 The private sector needs to have certainty in terms of where we are going in order to make the investments.

383
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:42,000
 And when we are looking at the total investment required in Europe to do the energy transition, we are talking about 4 trillion euros in this case.

384
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:45,000
 Three quarters of that has to come from the private sector.

385
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:53,000
 And what is there also needed is much stronger action on a capital market union because these funds need to be raised.

386
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:56,000
 Europe is still very fragmented in terms of raising capital.

387
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:02,000
 If we want to compete with the U.S. in Europe, the U.S. has fantastic capital markets.

388
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:06,000
 Europe needs to push there in order to help the private sector to finance.

389
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:11,000
 Jan, I want to turn to you because the fragmentation, we can tackle this from a number of angles.

390
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:25,000
 If you consider large chunks of the region, from the Czech Republic, Poland, Bosnia, Herzegovia, Serbia, Bulgaria, a lot of these countries still rely on fossil fuels versus others that are pivoted to say hydro, others using nuclear.

391
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:28,000
 It's a very different playing field across the board.

392
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:34,000
 A lot of these countries, I mean, Slovakia, a great example, large chunks of GDP are derived from fossil fuel industries.

393
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:43,000
 No guarantee that they'll be the forefront of industry down the track around electric vehicles unless there is a transition that works for that country.

394
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:50,000
 How do we think about ensuring all the nations in lockstep are moving together and that fragmentation doesn't deepen?

395
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:51,000
 Right.

396
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:59,000
 So look, they definitely want to move alongside with Europe and the rest of the world towards a greener, healthier way.

397
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:06,000
 But yes, they are starting from a point where they indeed are relying very much still on coal, oil and so on.

398
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:17,000
 So that's going to be a big transition where they themselves have to start acting more decisively and Europe as a whole has to be instrumental in enabling them to do so.

399
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:27,000
 In the midst of all of this, we have to realize that these huge investments that we are talking about are taking place when the debt of all these countries indebtedness has increased.

400
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:34,000
 So to borrow even more and go further in that direction obviously has macroeconomic implications.

401
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:46,000
 And again, going back to the fact that Europe is a continent that's growing slower or does not perform as well as China or the United States over the last years and decades,

402
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:47,000
 is really crucial.

403
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:54,000
 So I think that these countries depend very much on Europe as a whole becoming more competitive and they moving along with it.

404
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:57,000
 I think a great example is Poland.

405
00:41:57,000 --> 00:42:01,000
 Poland has done so well over the last decades during the Great Recession.

406
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:04,000
 It didn't even go into a recession if you look at annual data.

407
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:07,000
 So yes, it is possible for these countries to do well.

408
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:12,000
 But they face a greater challenge in fact than the rest of Europe and than the rest of the world.

409
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:18,000
 So this is where some coordinated, concerted action is really important.

410
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:23,000
 Kristalina Gorgieva was talking about fiscal policies supporting the vulnerable.

411
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:32,000
 We've seen enormous fiscal policies in the form of subsidies handed out to protect mainly consumers but also businesses from high energy prices.

412
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:35,000
 What's the role of these expensive handouts in future?

413
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:38,000
 I think they have to become much more targeted.

414
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:41,000
 Alfred already mentioned it and I think that you see it all over.

415
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:48,000
 That yes, during the pandemic and with the war, et cetera, the first action needs to be decisive and is not necessarily targeted.

416
00:42:48,000 --> 00:43:02,000
 But I think now these types of measures will have to really target the very poor, enable businesses to grow, but businesses have to adjust and they are adjusting and operating in much more uncertain environments.

417
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:08,000
 I think we'll talk about investments in the next session, but precisely there is a question.

418
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:16,000
 Will they be able, will the private sector be able to undertake the type of investments together with the assistance of the public sector?

419
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:19,000
 And that's, I'm just not sure, frankly.

420
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:25,000
 I mean, I think Europe has incredible potential, but it has shown that it also is unable to realize it.

421
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:31,000
 I mean, take for example, let's remember in 2000, the so-called Lisbon Declaration and Agreement.

422
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:36,000
 Europe in 10 years will become technologically the most advanced region in the world, right?

423
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:39,000
 2010 came, it didn't happen.

424
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:42,000
 So the agreement was, it's going to be 2020.

425
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:45,000
 Well, we're past 2020 and we see where we are, right?

426
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:52,000
 So one has to, in some sense, really design strategies that are much more effective going forward in Europe.

427
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:54,000
 And this region is part of Europe.

428
00:43:54,000 --> 00:44:02,000
 So it will depend very much on what Europe as a whole is able to do and really, you know, become sort of the leading part of the world, which it can.

429
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:11,000
 I mean, Europe really has the human capital, it has the possibilities, it is handicapped as we see with this in terms of energy situation right now.

430
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:15,000
 But it can certainly tackle it if it proceeds smartly and smoothly.

431
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:19,000
 You say that these policies should be more targeted in future.

432
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:21,000
 We are rolling around to an election cycle.

433
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:26,000
 Spain is on the cusp of voting, again, much sooner than anticipated.

434
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:34,000
 Targeted can be used in very different manners in these countries that are trying to shore up an outcome when we've got fragmentation of politics.

435
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:35,000
 Yes, indeed.

436
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:51,000
 But on the other hand, I think the social cohesion, you know, political cohesion in these countries really depends on the bottom half of the population feeling that they are not losing or not losing too much, that they are benefiting in some sense from what's going on.

437
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:54,000
 And the political aspect is very crucial in that, yes.

438
00:44:54,000 --> 00:44:56,000
 Alfred, do you want to weigh in on this?

439
00:44:56,000 --> 00:44:57,000
 Yeah.

440
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:07,000
 You really want to protect the most vulnerable, and you don't want to waste precious fiscal resources by just spreading them out.

441
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:11,000
 So that I think we all agree, and I think governments agree too.

442
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:18,000
 But it's sometimes difficult to do, and it's just quicker and easier to do it all across.

443
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:20,000
 The same thing applies to subsidies.

444
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:27,000
 When I'm thinking about subsidies for enterprises, you want to go in there where there is market failure.

445
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:33,000
 You want to address infrastructure need in order to create an enabling environment for enterprises.

446
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:43,000
 You don't want to just open the floodgates and use fiscal resources very inefficiently.

447
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:49,000
 Because in the end, we have a fiscal constraint in Europe in more general.

448
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:53,000
 So you need to think about being targeted everywhere.

449
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:56,000
 I did promise to take some questions from the audience.

450
00:45:56,000 --> 00:45:58,000
 So we do have a microphone here.

451
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:01,000
 Does anyone want to pose a question to the audience?

452
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:08,000
 If so, please raise your hand and we will bring a microphone to you.

453
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:10,000
 It's a very intelligent audience here.

454
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:12,000
 So I'm assuming someone's going to want to jump in with a question.

455
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:13,000
 No pressure.

456
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:14,000
 Front row.

457
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:15,000
 Second row.

458
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:16,000
 Oh, we have a gentleman over here.

459
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:24,000
 If you can just state your name and where you're from too, so the audience has some context, please.

460
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:25,000
 Thank you.

461
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:26,000
 Nate Arnold from the IMF.

462
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:30,000
 I just wanted to ask a bit more about the Net Zero Industry Act.

463
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:39,000
 I know a lot of that is aimed at sort of streamlining regulatory and permitting processes, but most of those are national or even local competency.

464
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:45,000
 Can you just talk a little bit more about how you envision actually implementing that part of the Net Zero Industry Act?

465
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:48,000
 Well, thank you for the question.

466
00:46:48,000 --> 00:47:00,000
 Indeed, so in the Net Zero Act, there were a set of clean energy technologies that are identified, which are absolutely decisive for the transition to take place.

467
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:14,000
 And then the idea is to create a favorable regulatory environment, for instance, by accelerating permitting, by putting together the necessary skills which are required,

468
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:17,000
 because this is a factor that we sometimes underestimate.

469
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:23,000
 We can have the targets, you can have the policies, and then you don't have the people who are qualified to implement it.

470
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:32,000
 So the idea is to tackle it across the system and see what can be the barriers to the deployment of this clean energy technologies

471
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:38,000
 and create such a conducive environment within the European Union.

472
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:50,000
 Now, this piece of legislation is now being discussed, negotiated with the European Council, with the European Parliament, so we'll see where we land.

473
00:47:50,000 --> 00:48:05,000
 But clearly, the idea is to have a number of elements which will allow to have a more favorable context for clean energy technologies to be manufactured in the EU,

474
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:14,000
 while recognizing that we will have to have the partnerships that Olga mentioned, and that we cannot do it all by ourselves, right?

475
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:24,000
 If you look at the journeys in terms of energy transition that the whole world is engaging in, we see that the need for clean energy technologies is massive.

476
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:33,000
 So obviously, cooperation will be key, and the question is to identify where and with whom can we best cooperate.

477
00:48:33,000 --> 00:48:34,000
 Can I follow up on that?

478
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:44,000
 Fresh from a technology event, you know, speaking to all of the innovators in the space, and one of the views is that there's been so much cheap credit for so long.

479
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:52,000
 There have been so many players wading into this space, but nobody has scale, and that there's so much time spent on talking about solutions.

480
00:48:52,000 --> 00:49:02,000
 There's not the rolling forward with development, or the clock is ticking, we don't have scale in some of these new industries to make any difference at this point.

481
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:04,000
 How do you change that narrative?

482
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:16,000
 It's interesting, I've been faced with that same question earlier this week, in the sense that we have a number of excellent small and medium enterprises within Europe,

483
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:21,000
 which are there ready to make the next step and the next jump.

484
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:26,000
 And the issue there is that they may not have access to capital precisely.

485
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:27,000
 So the de-risking of it.

486
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:29,000
 So we need to look into that.

487
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:39,000
 It's something clearly that we do need because we have extremely good SMEs in these areas of clean energy technologies.

488
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:44,000
 So we need to identify what are the barriers and tackle them.

489
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:49,000
 And clearly this is an issue where we need to look into and act.

490
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:51,000
 Can I just chime in just half a second?

491
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:57,000
 I think a really specific unique area that doesn't get enough attention is some entities, especially in Europe,

492
00:49:57,000 --> 00:50:06,000
 some businesses that don't have a great credit rating, but they're legitimate, fantastic companies that have proven themselves to have developed all sorts of projects.

493
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:14,000
 Sometimes they have a hard time partnering with US businesses or financial institutions because they don't have that credit rating.

494
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:22,000
 So if there is some kind of EU level or a broader scale risk management, we have literally seen that be an impediment to some of the broader scale

495
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:30,000
 that's really scaling up these massive projects here when we're talking about specific companies that might just not have it look really great on paper,

496
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:34,000
 but they do have the expertise and they're legitimate and they're trustworthy.

497
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:36,000
 Peter, do you want to jump in on this as well?

498
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:40,000
 I mean, I was talking to the boss of one of your competitors in recent months.

499
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:48,000
 And while there's interest in these technologies, it's almost a slight eyebrow raise as to how it impacts the overall corporate

500
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:58,000
 because some of these activities are so small, they don't have any long-term impact at this point for revenue for a big business like yours.

501
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:07,000
 So it's very clear that the most rapid pace of decarbonization is occurring in the power sector with wind and solar.

502
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:10,000
 But you have to think what comes next.

503
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:16,000
 So whether that's decarbonizing home heating with heat pumps, hydrogen, biofuel, so forth.

504
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:23,000
 So I think a large corporation has to think not 5, 10, but more like 25, 30 years out.

505
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:27,000
 So if I look at what Shell's doing, we are looking at sustainable aviation fuel.

506
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:31,000
 It is considerably more expensive than the standard stuff.

507
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:38,000
 However, if we want to fly around the place and get anywhere close to net zero in 2050, we're going to need it.

508
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:41,000
 So we need to start thinking how can we drive down costs.

509
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:43,000
 Same with hydrogen.

510
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:49,000
 Now, I think I'd be doing the room a disservice if I said some of these things were going to completely transform the world in the next 10 years.

511
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:50,000
 I don't think they are.

512
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:52,000
 But over the next 30 years, who knows?

513
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:57,000
 And the fact is, if we don't start trying now, we definitely will not get there.

514
00:51:57,000 --> 00:51:59,000
 Sort of hoping and praying, right?

515
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:04,000
 I was talking to the CFO of Ryanair early in the week, and it was a very similar conversation,

516
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:08,000
 that these sustainable fuels are just not economical at this point.

517
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:14,000
 If you had to use them today, it would be hugely detrimental for the quarterly earnings that they produce.

518
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:18,000
 So something needs to change between now and execution down the track, right?

519
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:21,000
 How do you get that critical mass that we're talking about?

520
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:23,000
 How do you get the economies of scale?

521
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:29,000
 So you have drive from policymakers, so European Union mandates for something like sustainable aviation fuel.

522
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:35,000
 But also, I don't want to offend anybody, but I'm not big on praying for this sort of thing.

523
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:37,000
 I'm much more on investing in R&D.

524
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:39,000
 And we will surprise ourselves.

525
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:40,000
 We always have done.

526
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:42,000
 I work in Shell Scenario Department.

527
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:43,000
 We try and think about the future.

528
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:48,000
 If I look back at what my predecessors have done, we always miss technological breakthroughs.

529
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:53,000
 I don't know where they're going to come from, but I'm confident that we will find them if we invest.

530
00:52:53,000 --> 00:52:59,000
 So in particularly decarbonizing industry and aviation and certain areas of heavy road transport,

531
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:03,000
 we need to be experimenting and seeing what works.

532
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:04,000
 It's no good trying to predict.

533
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:09,000
 We just try different things, and then something will emerge.

534
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:11,000
 We can take some more questions from the audience.

535
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:17,000
 Does anyone else want to chime in with a question or a comment on some of the discussion points that we've been having here?

536
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:19,000
 Feel free to raise your hand.

537
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:24,000
 Okay, we'll kick it back over here.

538
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:26,000
 We've got plenty more to discuss then.

539
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:29,000
 But if you do want to get involved, please do raise your hand.

540
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:31,000
 Do we have one?

541
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:33,000
 Oh, fantastic.

542
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:38,000
 Again, I'll ask you to state your name, please.

543
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:39,000
 Yes.

544
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:45,000
 Romain Duval from the IMF2, which is why I didn't want to ask a question, but you know.

545
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:50,000
 I have a question for Olga, which is regarding the prospects rate for gas next winter.

546
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:56,000
 There was a slight difference of view maybe with Alfred.

547
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:04,000
 And so, you know, what's your, you know, thinking about the likelihood of shortages vis-à-vis a renewed price spike, right?

548
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:08,000
 I think lots of the factors you listed would, you know, lead to a renewed price spike.

549
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,000
 But do you also see any kind of risk of shortages?

550
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:22,000
 Because, you know, I think our assessment was more that you would take, you know, a combination of risks to materialize for any shortages to, right, to materialize next winter.

551
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:24,000
 So is that also your assessment on that?

552
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:25,000
 Yeah.

553
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:28,000
 So, I mean, I think there's two different risks, right?

554
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:36,000
 There's risks around the price spikes, but there being enough gas in Europe because Europe would be able to purchase enough gas on the global market and attract enough supplies.

555
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:43,000
 But are really, really high price, just like we've seen over the last year, especially in August, right?

556
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:45,000
 Really expensive, but the supplies were here.

557
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:47,000
 So, overall, there was enough gas.

558
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:48,000
 Just really, really expensive.

559
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:53,000
 And you had to have all of these different national and EU-level schemes to support businesses and households.

560
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:54,000
 So there is that risk.

561
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:59,000
 There's also, like, overall shortage if you do get enough demand pulled in Asia.

562
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:10,000
 If there are some, you know, we have another Freeport situation where there are some exporting facilities that are not working for whatever reason, there's always that risk as well.

563
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:17,000
 But I think the pricing risk is always higher for Europe because there's still regionality around the markets, even within Europe.

564
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:25,000
 And when you have differences in prices, and you have differences in prices when you don't have fully fluid infrastructure, right?

565
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:30,000
 So that means that there is still a risk for internal competition across Europe.

566
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:36,000
 And there is still -- and this doesn't get talked about enough -- there is still a risk around competition for storage.

567
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:39,000
 You know, over 100 BCM of storage Europe, which is fantastic.

568
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:49,000
 But there isn't, you know, a guarantee in terms of how equitably that will be spread out and purchased across Europe if things get really, really tough.

569
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:54,000
 We didn't get to that point last winter because we didn't have to, and we came out with really high storage levels.

570
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,000
 But I do see a worst-case scenario now.

571
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:57,000
 This is really, really bad.

572
00:55:57,000 --> 00:55:58,000
 Like, everything going wrong.

573
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:01,000
 All of the things that I've mentioned, a couple of those things going wrong at the same time.

574
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:03,000
 I'm hoping that we don't get to that.

575
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:06,000
 I'm hoping that everything goes smoothly again.

576
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:18,000
 But there is a scenario where maybe countries that have more resources will be able to have access to that storage, these supplies, perhaps slightly easier than some of the other countries that are -- that don't have the same financial backing.

577
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:24,000
 We've mentioned the lack of Chinese demand and how that's taken some heat off the price.

578
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:27,000
 But we haven't mentioned the lack of German demand.

579
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:36,000
 And if we think about what played out last winter, in Germany, the Bundestag drew up blueprints on how to wind down certain industries.

580
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:37,000
 Heating was turned down.

581
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:45,000
 But the pointy end of this was that we could see large-scale shutdowns across industry if prices got out of control.

582
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:47,000
 We didn't quite get to that point.

583
00:56:47,000 --> 00:57:02,000
 And now the Germans are talking about an electricity subsidy that changes the playing field where manufacturing, industry, consumers have access to cheap energy at a price that could be different from the rest of Europe.

584
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:06,000
 What does that do as we talk about fragmentation of this policy moves forward?

585
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:11,000
 So there's always risk when you do have these different pricing schemes.

586
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:20,000
 And I think for Germany, it's a very unique case because the demand destruction that led to businesses shutting down or scaling down production, that should not be celebrated.

587
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:22,000
 I think it should be celebrated in terms of the solidarity.

588
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:27,000
 Yes, we got through last winter, but that is not -- that should never be the long-term goal, long-term solution.

589
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:37,000
 In the long-term, we should figure out a way to keep these businesses running, even when there are price spikes, even when the market situation gets tough.

590
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:48,000
 So the fragmentation in terms of national support, that's why I agree with the comments earlier in terms of the long-term goal is to get back to that competitive, integrated, interconnected market across Europe.

591
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:56,000
 All the efforts that were done over the last several decades through the third energy package and all the other -- and, of course, they had to be scaled back because we had an extremely tough year.

592
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:01,000
 Last year, last year, last 15, 16 months, some of the companies became nationalized.

593
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:05,000
 Some of these structures had to come in place to support businesses.

594
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:16,000
 But there is that risk when you have national support schemes that are different, that incentivize different production, different sources.

595
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:23,000
 And it is more confusing for the private sector in terms of even coming in and saying -- even predictability, even long-term investments.

596
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:25,000
 So great, you have that support scheme right now.

597
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:32,000
 But what does that mean for 5, 10, 15, 20 years if you're a private sector and you're looking into a specific project, right?

598
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:33,000
 Yeah, it's a good point.

599
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:38,000
 I mean, the ownership structure has changed on major companies from EDF to Uniper over the course of this time.

600
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:40,000
 But I know you both want to jump in.

601
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:41,000
 Please.

602
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:45,000
 Quickly, one of the biggest achievements in Europe is the creation of the single market.

603
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:53,000
 And that calls, when it comes to energy policy, energy security policy, it calls for European solutions.

604
00:58:53,000 --> 00:59:05,000
 And an element when we are looking at financing climate change in order also to deal with fiscal constraints is a climate fund, one should think about, which is addressing common infrastructural issues.

605
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:13,000
 But also is putting the euro where you get most out of it in terms of decarbonization.

606
00:59:13,000 --> 00:59:16,000
 So preserve the single market.

607
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:17,000
 Don't go alone.

608
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:20,000
 Don't fragment Europe.

609
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:22,000
 And we need a European solution for that.

610
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:26,000
 So are you saying Germany should avoid this electricity subsidy?

611
00:59:26,000 --> 00:59:32,000
 I think we should be very careful in general when we are thinking about subsidies.

612
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:34,000
 They have a place.

613
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:38,000
 But subsidies provide a particular incentive.

614
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:41,000
 Subsidies over a very long time are questionable.

615
00:59:41,000 --> 00:59:42,000
 Paula?

616
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:55,000
 Yes, and this is precisely what we, well, last year we put into place a set of emergency measures, as I said, including in terms of what types of schemes and subsidies could be put into place

617
00:59:55,000 --> 00:59:57,000
 in a context of emergency.

618
00:59:57,000 --> 01:00:05,000
 And now we are precisely looking into what are the measures that need to still be prolonged, because we are not out of the crisis yet.

619
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:12,000
 And we are, for gas, we have actually prolonged the gas demand reduction regulation for another year.

620
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:16,000
 For electricity, we are now coming out with a proposal on how to go about it.

621
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:25,000
 But we also learned the lessons and we have put on the table the electricity market design proposal, which is precisely to address in a structure

622
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:53,000
 manner how to go about this and to make sure that we do not have this fragmentation across the EU and that we are actually speaking of a genuine single market in terms of electricity, where we allow regulated prices only under exceptional circumstances when certain conditions are met, and that we create the conditions, for instance, through context for difference, to integrate the renewables more and more in the system in a level playing field.

623
01:00:53,000 --> 01:01:05,000
 So that's where we bring in and now are looking into what are the structural measures that need to be there precisely to also allow for investment certainty and for a level playing field across the EU.

624
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:09,000
 So what would you say to Chancellor Schultz about the electricity subsidy?

625
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:21,000
 We are in discussions on all of those measures which require state aid and which need to go through the appreciation of colleagues in the European Commission so clearly.

626
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:27,000
 It's something that we are looking into, not just for Germany, but for all those who are looking into it.

627
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:29,000
 It's a diplomatic language on stage at the moment.

628
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:30,000
 Jan.

629
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:35,000
 I think we have to be ready for major price fluctuations.

630
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:41,000
 They were in the past, they recently, and so, you know, be ready for price increases.

631
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:48,000
 I think that governments and EU in particular can smooth, provide some smoothing over time, but otherwise there has to be restructuring.

632
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:57,000
 And so, for instance, the fact that Europe still doesn't have an integrated capital market, even banks are basically country by country, that's been known for a long time.

633
01:01:57,000 --> 01:02:03,000
 Politically, there hasn't been any significant sufficient will really to move in that direction.

634
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:10,000
 And I think it's time to consider those kinds of issues as part of the energy strategy going forward.

635
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:20,000
 That, indeed, the US has been more successful because its private sector capital is moving faster, smoother to places where it needs to go.

636
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:30,000
 In Europe, we don't have it, and unless Europe takes concrete steps of that kind, it will not be able to face the challenge as well as other parts of the world.

637
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:38,000
 It's a very challenging crossroads where we talk about intervention, what's the right sort of intervention, what's too much, and what destabilizes market forces.

638
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:45,000
 The managing director just a moment so early before the session pointed out carbon pricing, that she was encouraging it.

639
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:48,000
 What does that do to market forces? Is it the right move?

640
01:02:48,000 --> 01:02:49,000
 I think that will be the right move.

641
01:02:49,000 --> 01:02:57,000
 I think it's a political question whether it can be adopted, but having a carbon tax, carbon pricing, I think is exactly the right way to go.

642
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:02,000
 And forcing and forging agreement on that would be a major step forward.

643
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:07,000
 Why doesn't it just add more complexity around doing business in Europe?

644
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:09,000
 Well, actually, it would simplify things.

645
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:16,000
 I think if people know and understand that there is a price, and price that is to a significant extent predictable,

646
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:22,000
 I think that will make private sector be more efficient and able to make the big investments that were mentioned.

647
01:03:22,000 --> 01:03:23,000
 Olga?

648
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:31,000
 So, I think, first of all, it starts at the accounting and having a global system where we can agree on how we're counting carbon emissions,

649
01:03:31,000 --> 01:03:37,000
 whether it's LNG, whether it's, you know, methane, whatever it is, or products that are being shipped to Europe and from Europe.

650
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:50,000
 With CBAM coming online, I actually think that could trigger, almost force a global way to start counting carbon emissions for certain products that perhaps have not been as clearly assessed in the past,

651
01:03:50,000 --> 01:03:59,000
 and force us to, in a way, to start applying that carbon pricing in an indirect way, even places like United States.

652
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:00,000
 It's actually interesting.

653
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:13,000
 There is some bipartisan support for it in U.S. in some corners, but it's not something that will be popular across all voters to get it across the line anytime soon on the U.S. side.

654
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:16,000
 But I think, once again, it starts with accounting.

655
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:23,000
 And you have to be able to count carbon emissions from the different products and the value chains in order to have a meaningful conversation.

656
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:28,000
 And we still, globally, do not have those standards on how to count, verify, and report.

657
01:04:28,000 --> 01:04:35,000
 Peter, business loves regulation. Carbon prices, a good thing?

658
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:43,000
 It's very difficult to imagine getting something like carbon capture and storage moving without carbon prices, in some way, shape, or form.

659
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:48,000
 I think the key thing, which has been mentioned, is the durability, the outlook for the price.

660
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:57,000
 If we'd all been sitting here a few years ago, European trading scheme was, you know, in the teens of euros, there wasn't really a price signal in the U.S.

661
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:02,000
 Today, you have the 45Q in the U.S. at $85 a tonne.

662
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:06,000
 You have the EU ETS at somewhere in the 80 euros per tonne.

663
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:10,000
 That's starting to make carbon capture and storage look interesting.

664
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:15,000
 It's incentivizing moves in the power system away from fossil towards renewables.

665
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:16,000
 It works.

666
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:19,000
 The question is, will it be there for the next 10, 20 years?

667
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:27,000
 I can see everybody's needing a bit of caffeine and sunshine, so I'm just going to get a quick takeaway message from our panelists today.

668
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:29,000
 We've had a very broad discussion.

669
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:36,000
 Something that you just want to leave the audience with, something you want to highlight about the challenge, the risk, something to think about from here.

670
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:38,000
 Olga, do you want to kick it off for us?

671
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:39,000
 Sure.

672
01:05:39,000 --> 01:05:40,000
 30 seconds.

673
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:41,000
 Yeah.

674
01:05:41,000 --> 01:05:53,000
 We haven't talked about Ukraine, which I think is a missed opportunity for this conversation in terms of kind of what's happening right now and how Ukraine can support European energy security and climate goals in the long term.

675
01:05:53,000 --> 01:06:07,000
 Tremendous nuclear expertise, tons of natural gas resources, a lot of, you know, areas where you can try out new technologies and innovation, but it needs support in the short term to maintain the institutions, maintain the energy sector functioning.

676
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:13,000
 So just and kind of thinking through that robust natural gas system in Ukraine, you know, what do you do with that in the future?

677
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:19,000
 How do you integrate maybe cleaner, lower carbon fuels into it that can support then clean energy transition in Europe as well?

678
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:33,000
 So I just want to make sure that we don't forget about that and then we support Ukraine in the short term and cooperate on that and also think through the big ambitious reconstruction goals for the clean and not just reconstruction, but transformation of the energy sector in Ukraine.

679
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:35,000
 Jan, see if you can top that.

680
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:46,000
 No, I would say, look, Europe is facing a much greater challenge and this part of Europe in particular than many other countries, U.S. in particular, has been thinking about it.

681
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:49,000
 It's been taking steps in the direction of how to solve it.

682
01:06:49,000 --> 01:07:00,000
 So in a way it's ahead and it's up to Europe in particular to sort of chart the direction and take some of the major steps, hopefully in coordination with the United States and other countries.

683
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:07,000
 And I think, as we mentioned in the conversation, China will be a crucial player, is a crucial player and will be an even more crucial player.

684
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:08,000
 Alfred.

685
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:09,000
 Yeah.

686
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:12,000
 Climate change is a global problem.

687
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:20,000
 That means we need to have a discussion globally on policy and we need to harmonize and talk about those.

688
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:26,000
 Second part, when you look at energy security, supply chain security, diversification is key.

689
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:31,000
 Whenever you fragment, it's becoming risky and becoming more expensive.

690
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:34,000
 Third, Europe has the single market.

691
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:36,000
 That single market needs to be protected.

692
01:07:36,000 --> 01:07:48,000
 More can be done, banking union, capital markets union, in order to allow small and medium enterprises to get capital in order to do these important climate investments.

693
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:57,000
 More needs to be done at the European level because energy security, energy transition, it's not a national problem, needs to be handled much more at the European level.

694
01:07:57,000 --> 01:07:58,000
 And Paula.

695
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:03,000
 Well, over the last year we saw impossible things made possible.

696
01:08:03,000 --> 01:08:09,000
 We have phased out fossil fuels from Russia in a way that nobody could have believed a year ago.

697
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:12,000
 We have accelerated the energy transition.

698
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:28,000
 And with Ukraine, we even went for synchronization of the electricity grid of Ukraine and Moldova with the EU in something that was not foreseen immediately and did happen to a point that Ukraine is in a possibility and has exported electricity to the EU.

699
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:30,000
 Many may not know this.

700
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:32,000
 So we made impossible things happen.

701
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:45,000
 I want us to all learn the lessons and we have to learn the lessons also for the energy security of the future, which is not fossil fuel related, but also not to commit the same mistakes that we did in terms of non-diversification.

702
01:08:45,000 --> 01:09:01,000
 Now we have to look into that precisely with the critical raw materials, with the critical minerals and ensure that we have the necessary grid in time to make this vision a reality.

703
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:02,000
 Thank you very much.

704
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:03,000
 What a terrific discussion.

705
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:09,000
 Now, before we wrap up, I'm just going to tell you whereabouts you're going, what's happening in your foreseeable future.

706
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:11,000
 We're taking a coffee break now.

707
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:14,000
 So that'll be roughly about 30 minutes.

708
01:09:14,000 --> 01:09:17,000
 There is a second panel that will start at 11:50.

709
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:18,000
 So just take a look at your watches.

710
01:09:18,000 --> 01:09:20,000
 11:50, we're back in here.

711
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:26,000
 But also there's a lovely big group photo, a moment in history that'll be on the terrace straight away now.

712
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:30,000
 So if you can wander out that way, but please put your hands together for the panel.

713
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:32,000
 Thank you so much to Alfred, Jan, Paula and Olga.

714
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:33,000
 Thank you so much to Alfred, Jan, Paula and Olga.

715
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:34,000
 Thank you so much to Alfred, Jan, Paula and Olga.

716
01:09:34,000 --> 01:09:35,000
 Thank you so much to Alfred, Jan, Paula and Olga.

717
